{"title_page": "Albert Sharpe", "text_new": "{{about|the actor|the American football and basketball player and coach|Albert Sharpe (American football)}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Albert Sharpe\n| image              = Albert Sharpe in Royal Wedding.jpg\n| caption            = in ''[[Royal Wedding]]'' (1951)\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1885|4|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Belfast]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|UK]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1970|2|13|1885|4|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n}}\n'''Albert Sharpe''' (15 April 1885 \u2013 13 February 1970) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] stage and film actor. \n\n==Life and work==\nAlbert Sharpe was born in [[Belfast]] where he attended [[St Mary's Christian Brothers' Grammar School, Belfast|St. Mary's Christian Brothers Grammar School]].\n\nHis most famous roles were those of Darby O'Gill in Disney's ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]'' and as Finian McLonergan in the Original Broadway production of the musical ''[[Finian's Rainbow]]''.<ref name=allmoviebio/><ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=spQ751Sv7TUC&pg=PT1277&lpg=PT1277&dq=abbey+theatre+dublin+albert+sharpe&source=bl&ots=B1cC98fXtC&sig=ACfU3U0dQzIBegvgVGhjwSIOywHFiQPRRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiiufbIkOXoAhXagVwKHSmrCTcQ6AEwAnoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=abbey%20theatre%20dublin%20albert%20sharpe&f=false</ref> (the film version, made in 1968, had [[Fred Astaire]] in the role.) On screen he played Fiona's father Andrew in the MGM musical [[Brigadoon (film)|Brigadoon]].<ref>https://www.allmovie.com/movie/brigadoon-v7124/cast-crew</ref> He was also a member of the [[Abbey Players]].<ref name=allmoviebio>https://www.allmovie.com/artist/albert-sharpe-p64875</ref> \n\nHis last ten years were spent in retirement. He died in 1970 in Belfast at the age of 84.<ref>https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba392346c</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[1946 in film|1946]]\n| ''[[I See a Dark Stranger]]''\n| Irish Publican\n| aka \"''The Adventuress''\" (USA). Uncredited\n|-\n| [[1947 in film|1947]]\n| ''[[Odd Man Out]]''\n| Bus Conductor\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[1948 in film|1948]]\n| ''[[Up in Central Park (film)|Up in Central Park]]''\n| Timothy Moore\n|\n|- \n| ''[[The Return of October]]''\n| Vince the Tout\n| aka \"''A Date with Destiny''\" (UK)\n|-\n| ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]''\n| Moore\n| aka \"''Jennie''\" (UK) OR \"''Tidal Wave''\"\n|-\n| [[1949 in film|1949]]\n| ''[[Adventure in Baltimore]]''\n| Dan Fletcher\n| aka \"''Bachelor Bait''\" (UK)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[1951 in film|1951]]\n| ''[[Royal Wedding]]''\n| James Ashmond\n| aka \"''Wedding Bells''\" (UK)\n|-\n| ''[[The Highwayman (1951 film)|The Highwayman]]''\n| Forsythe\n|\n|-\n| ''[[You Never Can Tell (1951 film)|You Never Can Tell]]''\n| Grandpa Hathaway\n| aka \"''One Never Knows''\" OR \"''You Never Know''\" (UK)\n|-\n| [[1952 in film|1952]]\n| ''[[Face to Face (1952 film)|Face to Face]]''\n| First Mate Brown\n| ('The Secret Sharer')\n|-\n| [[1954 in film|1954]]\n| ''[[Brigadoon (film)|Brigadoon]]''\n| Andrew Campbell\n|\n|-\n| [[1959 in film|1959]]\n| ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]''\n| Darby O'Gill\n| \n|-\n| [[1960 in film|1960]]\n| ''[[The Day They Robbed the Bank of England]]''\n| Tosher\n| (final film role)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0789185}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharpe, Albert}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Donaldson Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at St. Mary's Christian Brothers' Grammar School, Belfast]]\n[[Category:Irish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Irish male stage actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the actor|the American football and basketball player and coach|Albert Sharpe (American football)}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Albert Sharpe\n| image              = Albert Sharpe in Royal Wedding.jpg\n| caption            = in ''[[Royal Wedding]]'' (1951)\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1885|4|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Belfast]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|UK]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1970|2|13|1885|4|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n}}\n'''Albert Sharpe''' (15 April 1885 \u2013 13 February 1970) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] stage and film actor. \n\n==Life and work==\nAlbert Sharpe was born in [[Belfast]] where he attended [[St Mary's Christian Brothers' Grammar School, Belfast|St. Mary's Christian Brothers Grammar School]].\n\nHis most famous roles were those of Darby O'Gill in Disney's ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]'' and as Finian McLonergan in the Original Broadway production of the musical ''[[Finian's Rainbow]]''.<ref name=allmoviebio/><ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=spQ751Sv7TUC&pg=PT1277&lpg=PT1277&dq=abbey+theatre+dublin+albert+sharpe&source=bl&ots=B1cC98fXtC&sig=ACfU3U0dQzIBegvgVGhjwSIOywHFiQPRRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiiufbIkOXoAhXagVwKHSmrCTcQ6AEwAnoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=abbey%20theatre%20dublin%20albert%20sharpe&f=false</ref> (the film version, made in 1968, had [[Fred Astaire]] in the role.) On screen he played Fiona's father Andrew in the MGM musical [[Brigadoon (film)|Brigadoon]].<ref>https://www.allmovie.com/movie/brigadoon-v7124/cast-crew</ref> He was also a member of the Abbey Players.<ref name=allmoviebio>https://www.allmovie.com/artist/albert-sharpe-p64875</ref> \n\nHis last ten years were spent in retirement. He died in 1970 in Belfast at the age of 84.<ref>https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba392346c</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[1946 in film|1946]]\n| ''[[I See a Dark Stranger]]''\n| Irish Publican\n| aka \"''The Adventuress''\" (USA). Uncredited\n|-\n| [[1947 in film|1947]]\n| ''[[Odd Man Out]]''\n| Bus Conductor\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[1948 in film|1948]]\n| ''[[Up in Central Park (film)|Up in Central Park]]''\n| Timothy Moore\n|\n|- \n| ''[[The Return of October]]''\n| Vince the Tout\n| aka \"''A Date with Destiny''\" (UK)\n|-\n| ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]''\n| Moore\n| aka \"''Jennie''\" (UK) OR \"''Tidal Wave''\"\n|-\n| [[1949 in film|1949]]\n| ''[[Adventure in Baltimore]]''\n| Dan Fletcher\n| aka \"''Bachelor Bait''\" (UK)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[1951 in film|1951]]\n| ''[[Royal Wedding]]''\n| James Ashmond\n| aka \"''Wedding Bells''\" (UK)\n|-\n| ''[[The Highwayman (1951 film)|The Highwayman]]''\n| Forsythe\n|\n|-\n| ''[[You Never Can Tell (1951 film)|You Never Can Tell]]''\n| Grandpa Hathaway\n| aka \"''One Never Knows''\" OR \"''You Never Know''\" (UK)\n|-\n| [[1952 in film|1952]]\n| ''[[Face to Face (1952 film)|Face to Face]]''\n| First Mate Brown\n| ('The Secret Sharer')\n|-\n| [[1954 in film|1954]]\n| ''[[Brigadoon (film)|Brigadoon]]''\n| Andrew Campbell\n|\n|-\n| [[1959 in film|1959]]\n| ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]''\n| Darby O'Gill\n| \n|-\n| [[1960 in film|1960]]\n| ''[[The Day They Robbed the Bank of England]]''\n| Tosher\n| (final film role)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0789185}}\n*{{IBDB 